{% block content %}
  <h2>Through your nation: band post-secondary funding</h2>
  <p>Your nation's education office administers federal post-secondary funding (the Post-Secondary Student Support Program, PSSSP, and the entrance-preparation program, UCEP). It can help cover tuition, books, travel, and a living allowance. You apply through your nation's education office, not to the government directly, and each nation sets its own deadlines and decides who is funded. This money is limited and capped, so not every student is funded each year and partial funding is common. Receiving it does not block you from federal or provincial student aid, so apply for those too.</p>
  <p class="muted">Sources: <a href="https://www.sac-isc.gc.ca/eng/1100100033682/1531933580211" target="_blank" rel="noopener">PSSSP</a>, <a href="https://www.sac-isc.gc.ca/eng/1100100033688/1531936422341" target="_blank" rel="noopener">UCEP</a>, <a href="https://www.sac-isc.gc.ca/eng/1774356839325/1774356862403" target="_blank" rel="noopener">national guidelines</a>.</p>

  <h2>Ontario student aid: OSAP</h2>
  <p>OSAP is the Ontario government's aid program, a mix of grants you do not repay and loans you do. It is open to eligible Ontario residents and can be used alongside band funding. Ontario's own page says funding for Indigenous students may come through both your band and OSAP. Two Ontario awards are aimed at Indigenous students: the Indigenous Student Bursary, and the First Nations Resource Development Scholarship for students in mining-related programs. Apply online, and check the current application year.</p>
  <p class="muted">Sources: <a href="https://www.ontario.ca/page/osap-ontario-student-assistance-program" target="_blank" rel="noopener">OSAP</a>, <a href="https://www.ontario.ca/page/osap-for-under-represented-learners" target="_blank" rel="noopener">OSAP for under-represented learners</a>.</p>

  <h2>Indspire bursaries and scholarships</h2>
  <p>Indspire is a national Indigenous charity, separate from your band and from government. One application covers hundreds of bursaries and scholarships for First Nations, Inuit, and Metis students, and stays active across the year's deadlines. Because more people apply than can be funded, not everyone is funded, but it costs nothing to apply and it stacks on top of band funding. Confirm this year's deadlines on their page.</p>
  <p class="muted">Sources: <a href="https://indspire.ca/apply-now/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Indspire apply</a>, <a href="https://indspire.ca/programs/students/bursaries-scholarships/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">bursaries and scholarships</a>.</p>

  <h2>Skills, trades, and employment training (ISET)</h2>
  <p>If you want trades, a shorter program, a certificate, or job training, there is a separate funding stream from band post-secondary money: the federal Indigenous Skills and Employment Training (ISET) program, delivered by local Indigenous organizations. It can fund things band post-secondary funding often will not, and it serves members on and off reserve. You contact your regional holder:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>North Shore nations, including Sagamok Anishnawbek: Mamaweswen, The North Shore Tribal Council (ISETP). <a href="https://mamaweswen.com/7946/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">mamaweswen.com</a></li>
    <li>Manitoulin UCCMM nations: Mnidoo Mnising Employment and Training. <a href="http://www.uccmm.ca/mnidoo-mnising-employment--training.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">uccmm.ca</a></li>
    <li>Wiikwemkoong: Wii-ni n'guch-tood Labour Market Services.</li>
    <li>Metis citizens: Metis Nation of Ontario, Education and Training. <a href="https://www.metisnation.org/programs-and-services/education-training/metis-employment-programs/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">metisnation.org</a></li>
    <li>To find any other holder: <a href="https://www.canada.ca/en/employment-social-development/programs/indigenous-skills-employment-training.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">ISET program and find-a-holder</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Apprenticeship and the trades</h2>
  <p>You learn a trade in Ontario as a paid apprentice: you work, attend in-class training, and earn a certificate. Ontario supports include a tools grant and the Apprentice Development Benefit for living and travel costs during in-class training, and the federal Canada Apprentice Loan offers interest-free loans. Note: the older federal Apprenticeship Incentive Grant and Completion Grant closed in March 2025, so ignore older guides that mention them.</p>
  <p class="muted">Sources: <a href="https://www.ontario.ca/page/start-apprenticeship" target="_blank" rel="noopener">start an apprenticeship (Ontario)</a>, <a href="https://www.canada.ca/en/services/jobs/training/support-skilled-trades-apprentices/grants.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">federal apprentice supports</a>.</p>

  <h2>Search every Indigenous bursary</h2>
  <p>Indigenous Services Canada runs a free search tool listing bursaries, scholarships, and incentives from across the country. Worth a scan before you assume there is nothing for your situation.</p>
  <p class="muted">Source: <a href="https://www.sac-isc.gc.ca/eng/1351185180120/1351685455328" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Indigenous Bursaries Search Tool</a>.</p>

  <h2>If your nation turns you down</h2>
  <p>Band post-secondary funding is capped, so a no is often about the cap, not about you. Fair questions to ask your education office: how the selection formula works, how many seats there are this year, when the deadline is, whether you can reapply next intake, and whether partial funding is possible. While you wait, OSAP, Indspire, ISET, and the bursary search above do not depend on the band's decision.</p>

